# {{lb|en|Wiktionary and WMF jargon}} The [[wiki]] [[software]] used by many websites, including the [[Wikimedia]] projects such as [[Wikipedia]], [[w:Wiktionary|Wiktionary]], etc.
#* {{quote-book|author=Tim Jowers|year=2006|isbn=1430301015|title=The Business Guide to Free Information Technology|page=59|publisher=LuLu Press|passage='''MediaWiki''' is the most well-known wiki software because it is what runs WikiPedia. MediaWiki is simple to use and an excellent way to start collaborating on documentation or articles.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Mark S. Choate|page=41|isbn=0470126906|publisher=Wiley Publishing|year=2007|title=Professional Wikis|passage=The architecture of '''MediaWiki''' is driven in large part by the idiosyncrasies of PHP. When MediaWiki was first developed, it used PHP 4.x, which lacked much in the way of object-oriented programming features.}}
#* {{quote-journal|url=http://www.informationweek.com/personal-tech/science-tech/lost-fans-find-internet-thrills-via-wiki/207401542|work={{w|InformationWeek}}|date=April 26, 2008|author=Mitch Wagner|title=Lost Fans Find Internet Thrills Via Wikis, Games, Second Life|accessdate=October 28, 2012|passage='''MediaWiki''' is the software platform underlying Wikipedia; he chose that software because he's "amazed and fascinated" with both Wikipedia and the software underlying it, he said. He wanted to learn more about building wikis, and thought Lostpedia was a good place to start.}}
#* {{quote-book|title=Wired for Learning: An Educator's Guide to Web 2.0|page=187|isbn=1607520966|year=2009|author=Terry T. Kidd, Irene Chen|publisher=Information Age Publishing, Inc.|passage=A notable irony of Wikipedia's popularity is that the editing process of its supporting technology, '''MediaWiki''', is complex to learn. Editing Wikipedia pages requires significant investment to learn MediaWiki's unique and powerful code structure.}}
#* {{quote-book|title=The Everything Guide to Social Media|page=166|isbn=1440506310|author=John K. Waters, John Lester|year=2010|publisher=F+W Media Inc.|passage=First released in 2002, '''MediaWiki''' is one of the top wiki engines and runs most of the wiki hosting sites. The name was a play on “Wikimedia,” and many people find it to be annoyingly confusing.}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Laura Lemay, Rafe Colburn|title=Sams Teach Yourself Web Publishing with HTML and CSS in One Hour a Day|publisher=Sams Publishing|year=2011|isbn=9780672330964|passage=The main downside of publishing a site using '''MediaWiki''' is that it won't give you a great opportunity to use or improve your HTML skills.}}
#* {{quote-journal|url=http://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/10/08/web_platform_docs_launch/|work={{w|The Register}}|title=Tech rivals team up for free web dev docs|author=Neil McAllister|date=October 8, 2012|publisher=www.theregister.co.uk|accessdate=October 28, 2012|passage=The site is based on Wikipedia's '''MediaWiki''' platform, which allows anyone to add or edit the available content, provided they register for an account using a verifiable email address.}}

